{"key":"processedPost-10187470","value":{"id":10187470,"first":10187315,"last":10187540,"when":1240028573,"utime":"04/18/09 07:22 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />but an alkaline PH 7-8 is good for primordia-<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Not so.<br /><br />Most mushroom species prefer an acidic substrate, as do most molds.&nbsp; The ONLY reason we lime casing layers is to make them less hospitable to mold spore germination, since the casing layer usually doesn't fully colonize.&nbsp; Established mycelium, whether mold or mushroom, can <i>tolerate</i> a high pH.&nbsp; It's only the spores that are inhibited from germination in a basic pH environment.&nbsp; Primordia are not stimulated by high pH.<br /><br />No bulk substrate ingredient is really any better than any other, if you take into account the species you're growing.&nbsp; Mushrooms like worm castings and they like coffee.&nbsp; They also like straw, dung, coir, etc., and perhaps best is to mix them all together in any quantity that you have them.&nbsp; It also helps to cut bulk substrates with vermiculite at up to 50% of the total substrate by volume.&nbsp; You don't lime substrates or worry about pH.&nbsp; You only lime casing layers for reasons stated above.<br />RR","title":"Re: Castings vs. Coffee + PH??","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}